WEBVTT

00:14.530 --> 00:22.523
All right, hello and welcome to the Petty Profit Podcast where we talk about news, culture and politics from a Christian worldview.

00:22.563 --> 00:25.467
It is the Tuesday show and I am glad you're here.

00:25.527 --> 00:27.150
Thanks for listening today.

00:27.190 --> 00:38.427
I'm gonna try to make this quick because I am currently in my little office covered in moving blankets, which is what helps deaden the sound in here.

00:38.588 --> 00:42.674
So it doesn't sound like I'm in a, you know, in the Grand Canyon or something.

00:42.818 --> 00:50.611
with a lot of echos, so it's really hot and I'm really uncomfortable, so I'm going to try to make this quick.

00:51.292 --> 01:01.911
And if you have feedback for the show, if you have an idea for another podcast episode, something you'd like to hear me or my brothers talk about, be sure to write in.

01:01.951 --> 01:05.777
You can reach me at contactathepetiprofit.com.

01:05.797 --> 01:08.562
Again, that's contactathepetiprofit.com.

01:08.642 --> 01:14.209
And if you love the show, if you want to support the show, the best thing you can do is go into iTunes and give it a five-star review.

01:14.249 --> 01:14.809
It really helps.

01:14.990 --> 01:16.351
And be sure to subscribe.

01:16.652 --> 01:20.496
We're available on iTunes, Spotify, Stitcher, Podbean, Castbox.

01:20.777 --> 01:26.604
Anywhere you get podcasts, you can subscribe and get updated whenever we release a new show.

01:26.844 --> 01:29.728
So without further delay, let's get into it.

01:36.015 --> 01:38.418
So I was kind of laughing as I

01:38.562 --> 01:42.927
prepared this episode because I was thinking about my dad.

01:42.967 --> 01:50.796
My dad is probably going to love this one because in this episode, I rail against mega churches just a little bit.

01:51.236 --> 02:00.466
I don't want to say a rail against them, but mega churches of seeker sensitive churches have always been a favorite target of my dad.

02:01.047 --> 02:02.408
So we'll probably get a kick out of this.

02:02.989 --> 02:03.890
And I don't want to knock

02:04.354 --> 02:10.380
You know, the big churches, the mega churches, the secret sensitive churches, because I do know that God uses them.

02:10.600 --> 02:12.782
God uses them in a mighty way oftentimes.

02:12.902 --> 02:22.992
And they've been effective at bringing people in and introducing people to the gospel who otherwise may never have stepped foot in a church.

02:23.072 --> 02:29.798
So, you know, I don't want to be, you know, nasty or combative or condemning in kind of my assessment here.

02:29.898 --> 02:34.002
But I think this talk is timely because

02:34.978 --> 02:40.965
Our culture is undergoing some tremendous upheaval right now.

02:41.686 --> 02:44.289
There is a lot of change happening.

02:44.650 --> 02:50.857
And I think some of these larger churches are struggling with how to respond to it.

02:51.938 --> 02:58.987
You know, churches that want to stay open, that want to stay relevant, that don't want to lose their thousands of members.

02:59.708 --> 03:03.092
You know, how do you respond to the Black Lives Matter movement?

03:03.172 --> 03:04.914
How do you respond to

03:05.186 --> 03:15.899
the pressure of critical race theory and intersectionality or LGBTQ ideology and theology or abortion.

03:16.580 --> 03:25.691
I don't envy any mega church pastor with a large following who has to deal with all of these issues and all of these questions.

03:28.755 --> 03:34.322
So I want to extend them as much grace as I can, but I had a few thoughts the other day.

03:34.626 --> 03:36.007
as I was reading the Gospels.

03:36.047 --> 03:37.669
I've been trying to read through the Gospels.

03:38.470 --> 03:44.976
I always find it's just kind of a great palate cleanser when we're in trying times like this.

03:45.837 --> 04:03.954
You open up the Bible, Matthew Mark Luke John, you read the words of Jesus and he speaks with such authority and he just cuts through so much of the crap and the noise that we hear from all sides all the time.

04:04.290 --> 04:11.441
One thing I've noticed in my reading of the Gospels was that Jesus was a PR nightmare.

04:13.484 --> 04:16.729
I mean, seriously, Jesus had 12 disciples.

04:16.810 --> 04:23.540
Couldn't he have chosen at least someone who was a communications expert to like smooth out the edges in his speeches?

04:23.560 --> 04:30.751
I mean, imagine how much more successful his earthly ministry could have been.

04:30.771 --> 04:32.434
I mean, okay, of course,

04:32.898 --> 04:51.301
I'm being facetious here, but I laugh to myself as I picture Simon Peter or Matthew, you know, slapping their foreheads when Jesus told his massive following that he had just, you know, just gathered to, you know, for example, eat his flesh and drink his blood.

04:51.341 --> 04:58.450
Or when he called the most respected religious authorities of that day, a brood of vipers.

04:59.010 --> 05:07.844
or when he promised to tear down the temple in Jerusalem in a cryptic prophecy of his resurrection that he knew many would misunderstand.

05:08.465 --> 05:17.058
You know, I imagine what it must have been like to listen to the teaching of Jesus as he preached the sermon on the Mount, for example.

05:18.300 --> 05:19.121
I read some of it today.

05:19.161 --> 05:27.474
I just kind of went through it and there are some hard teachings in the sermon on the Mount and you know,

05:28.162 --> 05:34.128
The book itself and Matthew, it records what the reaction to his sermon was.

05:34.168 --> 05:37.431
It says the crowds were astonished at his teaching.

05:37.451 --> 05:43.938
I just picture these people just with their mouths, a gape, their jaws on the floor after hearing what Jesus had said.

05:44.178 --> 05:48.763
Things like, if your right eye causes you to sin, gouge it out.

05:49.984 --> 05:53.848
If you get divorced and marry another, you're committing adultery.

05:55.189 --> 05:56.210
I'm imagining

05:56.482 --> 06:01.668
him saying something like that and a few people getting up and walking away, shaking their heads.

06:02.589 --> 06:09.196
Or, you know, Jesus goes on to say, if someone steals your shirt, give him your cloak as well.

06:09.576 --> 06:14.401
If a Roman soldier forces you to carry his gear for a mile, carry it for two.

06:15.142 --> 06:26.034
And I'm picturing people, you know, shaking their heads saying seriously, you know, give more to our evil Roman oppressors and, you know, a few more walk out angrily.

06:26.722 --> 06:33.309
And then he goes on to say, not everyone who says to me, Lord, Lord, we'll enter the kingdom of heaven.

06:33.949 --> 06:38.073
The way is narrow that leads to life and there are few that find it.

06:38.133 --> 06:54.930
And I picture that by the time Jesus has done with these talks, I am imagining this massive crowd that had initially gathered to see the healings and be fed and meet the Messiah who would lead the nation of Israel to her former glory.

06:55.106 --> 06:59.011
while they've now dwindled down to just a handful of people.

06:59.832 --> 07:14.493
You know, again and again in the scripture, we see Jesus' loving kindness and miracles attracting massive crowds, but as soon as he opens his mouth to deliver the message, the crowds start to dissipate.

07:15.794 --> 07:24.306
Sometimes when I read the Gospels and then look up from my Bible and think about the American church, I worry a little.

07:24.930 --> 07:27.453
Well, maybe worry is not the best word.

07:28.374 --> 07:30.257
Maybe I should say I ponder a little bit.

07:30.457 --> 07:40.711
I think about what's going on because American freedom has produced a thriving culture of business and leadership, best practices.

07:40.771 --> 07:49.522
We have become experts at creating a product, branding and marketing that product, drawing in customers, building empires.

07:49.602 --> 08:16.868
And, you know, in the business world, these practices have produced some incredible successes and have changed millions of lives, but they have also produced some incredibly influential churches, massive buildings, slick marketing, multiple campuses, millions of dollars, best-selling books, movies, Bible study programs, and more, all designed to draw in the customer and keep him or her in the seat.

08:16.888 --> 08:18.770
American capitalism.

08:18.914 --> 08:27.207
has led many dynamic, enterprising individuals to craft and produce a product around Christianity.

08:27.728 --> 08:33.557
These massive churches have become their own, you know, lifestyle brands, record labels, social clubs.

08:34.338 --> 08:36.181
And that's not to say that God hasn't used them.

08:36.241 --> 08:45.094
I mean, there are churches in my town that have such a well-done Sunday production, you know, professional music, slick marketing.

08:45.195 --> 08:47.378
It's impossible not to like them.

08:47.650 --> 08:50.557
It's impossible not to be drawn in by them.

08:50.597 --> 08:56.831
They launch marketing campaigns entitled things like, you know, you matter.

08:57.512 --> 09:06.994
You know, signs and billboards all over the town that say you matter or love no matter what, you know, messages that are graceful and winsome and pleasant.

09:07.266 --> 09:08.568
And it draws many in.

09:08.688 --> 09:09.530
And why wouldn't it?

09:09.730 --> 09:15.138
They are communicating, I mean, they are communicating an essential part of the gospel to a lost and dying world.

09:15.179 --> 09:18.904
The fact that they are made in the image of God, that they matter to God.

09:19.585 --> 09:21.489
And it does get people in the doors.

09:21.569 --> 09:23.872
And it's all cool and dynamic and exciting.

09:23.932 --> 09:35.090
But I fear these churches are headed towards a drop off or maybe a fork in the road, if you will.

09:36.258 --> 09:52.934
I think some of these churches are canoeing swiftly towards Niagara Falls because it's one thing to get people in the doors and it's a whole other thing to keep them there and our culture is changing.

09:54.355 --> 09:54.896
It's changing.

09:56.818 --> 09:58.599
And I think there is a gut check coming.

09:59.861 --> 10:03.524
I don't know if it will come soon or in 15 years.

10:04.265 --> 10:05.426
I don't know if it will come

10:05.570 --> 10:06.831
suddenly or gradually.

10:07.532 --> 10:22.106
In some ways, I think that gut check has already arrived because we are quickly coming to a place in this country, in our culture, where biblical Christianity is no longer civilized.

10:23.427 --> 10:35.218
It's no longer a creed held to openly by polite, culturally accepted people, especially when it comes to the issues most megachurch pastors only whisper to trusted friends about.

10:36.482 --> 10:39.186
I'm talking about issues like abortion.

10:41.270 --> 10:47.099
Really sticky ones like the LGBTQ theological and political agenda.

10:47.880 --> 11:00.541
I think most megachurch pastors, evangelical pastors still hold orthodox Christianity when it comes to these teachings on biblical sexuality and the value of preborn life, but they aren't very outspoken about it.

11:01.382 --> 11:03.986
They seem to prefer to stick with

11:04.130 --> 11:22.913
the uplifting messages that got the people in the doors in the first place, but the world and its progressive movements that continue to march forward will not let these churches get away with that for long, I don't think.

11:23.735 --> 11:32.946
I think for all of these churches, for all of us, there will come a day when stewards of these multi-million dollar church franchises will be forced

11:33.378 --> 11:51.207
to clearly and unequivocally declare either their support or their opposition to things like abortion, to gay affirming theology, to, quote, gospel supplements like critical race theory and intersectionality.

11:52.088 --> 12:00.562
And as always, there are always the more, shall we say, cantankerous and combative Christians that are the first

12:00.674 --> 12:02.938
to stand against these sweeping cultural movements.

12:02.978 --> 12:10.350
These churches love a good strong fight for the truth of the gospel, but sometimes they struggle in the grace department.

12:11.512 --> 12:27.378
Then, of course, on the opposite end of the spectrum, there are the most progressive churches and denominations that have already completely given themselves over to the tossing waves of culture, abandoning sound truth completely for a little credibility in the world's eyes.

12:28.610 --> 12:36.562
But then there is the massive middle, the mainstream of American evangelical Christianity.

12:36.582 --> 12:41.069
And what I see so far is not very encouraging.

12:42.451 --> 12:48.720
You know, we saw Carl Lentz of Hillsong shrink back when asked about abortion on the view.

12:49.721 --> 12:52.786
Should be the easiest question to answer.

12:53.570 --> 12:59.135
We're already seeing the anti-Gospel heresy of critical race theory ravaged the Southern Baptist Convention.

12:59.196 --> 13:06.943
We're already seeing influential Christian leaders affirm LGBTQ ideology and universalism.

13:07.784 --> 13:09.305
And should we be surprised?

13:09.906 --> 13:12.268
I mean, not if we look at history.

13:12.449 --> 13:22.098
I mean, look at how the vast majority of the German church got swept up in Hitler's ideology, many for fear of losing their congregations or their offices as pastors.

13:22.338 --> 13:29.550
Look how many churches in America fell prey to Darwinism and scientific racism and segregation in Jim Crow.

13:31.012 --> 13:38.704
If history is any indication to me, it doesn't bode well for the American church.

13:40.207 --> 13:42.550
So, what am I prescribing here?

13:43.211 --> 13:47.378
Am I saying we need to start being more, quote unquote, disagreeable?

13:47.778 --> 13:53.043
that we need to be nastier, more combative, more loud-mouthed as we stand up for the cause of truth.

13:53.664 --> 13:54.284
Of course not.

13:54.664 --> 13:55.185
Of course not.

13:55.225 --> 13:56.386
I'm not saying that at all.

13:57.647 --> 14:04.213
We know that Christians indwelt by the Holy Spirit must exude grace and gentleness and meekness.

14:04.954 --> 14:07.456
All I'm saying is that we need to be ready.

14:08.578 --> 14:17.586
We need to know what we believe, why we believe it, and what we would be willing to give up for it because

14:18.050 --> 14:23.577
I think a time may be approaching when we all may have to give up something.

14:25.159 --> 14:26.901
Are you willing to lose your job?

14:27.762 --> 14:28.383
Your friends?

14:29.464 --> 14:30.445
Your reputation?

14:30.846 --> 14:31.467
Your church?

14:31.827 --> 14:32.468
Your brand?

14:33.249 --> 14:47.026
I think the tragic truth is that in this massive cultural upheaval, there will be many church leaders who compromise the true gospel in order to remain loved, accepted, relevant, or

14:47.554 --> 14:48.495
physically stable.

14:50.057 --> 14:52.521
And they will take many poor souls with them.

14:53.122 --> 14:57.468
And they will try so hard, so hard to make the compromise they are making.

14:57.608 --> 15:00.051
Look legitimate, look biblical.

15:00.632 --> 15:06.220
And I think many of us will be appalled by what some churches teach as gospel in 10 years time.

15:06.821 --> 15:08.643
But here's the beautiful thing about this though.

15:10.486 --> 15:11.788
We don't have to worry about it.

15:12.449 --> 15:15.032
God promises he will build his church no matter what.

15:15.633 --> 15:16.434
The Lord and

15:16.514 --> 15:20.000
2 Timothy 2 19 tells us, he says, the Lord knows who are His.

15:20.060 --> 15:24.026
He will preserve the ones He has chosen in His infinite grace.

15:25.068 --> 15:35.485
Our only responsibility is to turn from wickedness, abide in the vine, walk with Him, obey Him, step by step, every day.

15:35.545 --> 15:41.074
And if we manage to do that, by the time we are called,

15:41.250 --> 15:55.710
sometime in the future if that day comes, to give up worldly possessions, status, and reputation for the sake of Christ, we won't really be all that attached to it anyway, because we will already have something much better.

15:56.471 --> 15:59.195
And you'll remember Jesus was given the same choice.

15:59.896 --> 16:09.650
Jesus was offered all the kingdoms and riches of the world, if only he would bow down and serve, for God, lowercase g, God, of this world.

16:10.082 --> 16:12.865
And we all know what Jesus ended up choosing.

16:13.526 --> 16:17.371
He chose the path of suffering and of slander and of pain.

16:17.411 --> 16:23.398
And in his most difficult of teachings, he promised his followers to expect the same.

16:23.939 --> 16:31.668
But then he promised in Matthew 1039 that the one who seeks his life will lose it, but the one who gives up his life because of me will find it.

16:32.489 --> 16:39.698
So every time I'm tempted to fret about the downward spiral of our country,

16:40.226 --> 16:57.348
and watch so much of the church spiral closely behind, I remember the truth, and I find myself even looking forward to those future experiences where I may be forced to cling to Christ more closely than I ever have before.

16:58.249 --> 16:59.130
It won't be a bad thing.

16:59.551 --> 17:00.452
It won't be a bad thing.

17:02.174 --> 17:04.457
So those are my words for today.

17:04.477 --> 17:08.402
It wasn't as quick as I thought it would be.

17:08.738 --> 17:12.527
I hope you enjoyed it anyway.

17:12.807 --> 17:15.434
So that is how I will leave it.

17:15.895 --> 17:16.997
I appreciate you listening.

17:17.057 --> 17:24.835
Don't forget to leave a review on iTunes and we will see you back here Thursday for another man hug with me and my brothers.

17:24.956 --> 17:25.657
Looking forward to it.

17:25.757 --> 17:26.579
Can't wait to see you there.

17:26.619 --> 17:27.762
Take care.

